\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. L. procumbens} (L.) Desv., {\i Jour. Bot. Appl.}{\b  1}: 35 (1813) ({\i Azalea procumbens} L.). Glabrous; stems procumbent, rooting, freely branched, forming extensive mats. Leaves 4-7 × 2 mm, oblong, obtuse; margins revolute; midrib prominent beneath. Bracts like the leaves but smaller and subacute; pedicels 2-8 mm. Sepals lanceolate, red. Corolla c. 4 × 6 mm, pink. Stamens shorter than corolla. Capsule 3-4 mm, red. 2n = 24.{\i  Dry, stony or peaty places, mainly on mountains, often in very exposed situations; calcifuge. N. Europe, southwards to} c. 56°{\i  N. in Scotland; mountains of France, Pyrenees, Alps, Carpathians.} Au Br Fa Fe Ga Ge He Hs Is It Ju No Rm Rs (N, W) Su.
